<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: POP/ROCK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG BRAXTON , Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Miriam Makeba Home at Last: Miriam Makeba, the South African-born singer hailed 
as "Mama Africa" for her passion and popularity, sang on home soil for the 
first time in 31 years Sunday after returning from political exile to visit 
family and her mother's grave in Johannesburg. The 57-year-old Makeba joined 
relatives, local entertainers and supporters in singing the black liberation 
anthem "Nkosi Sikele i'Afrika," or "God Bless Africa." She told reporters that 
she did not "sleep for a week" in anticipation of getting an entry visa, which 
was refused her until Friday. GREG BRAXTON 
</P>
