<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE STYLE IS DEMAGOGUE, BUT LACKING SERIOUSNESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MURRAY KEMPTON, Murray Kempton is a syndicated columnist in New York. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The day after his election as president of the Russian Republic, Boris Yeltsin 
promised: 
</P>
<P>
"If we last 100 days Russia will be independent . . . Russia's laws will take 
precedence over national laws. We should have our own interpretation of the 
laws on Russia's lands, on property, on the autonomy of enterprises. Treaties 
will be concluded with foreign states bypassing the center." 
</P>
<P>
The center that Yeltsin was proposing to set aside is the state apparatus that 
Mikhail Gorbachev struggles to administer. To read such stuff is scarcely to 
accord its author any place of special portent among the specters now haunting 
Gorbachev. 
</P>
<P>
For here is the style of the demagogue. The practice of demagoguery cannot be 
dismissed out of hand, since it is an elemental component of the democratic 
process. But, if he is to be taken seriously, the demagogue must not just 
befuddle the public but make some degree of sense to the managers of society. 
Yeltsin seems incapable of taking that necessity into account. His future is 
unpromising until he does. 
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has made himself the voice of the Great Russian chauvinism that most 
galls the Russian Federation's sister republics. The last census identified 800 
different nationalities in the Soviet Union. Yeltsin's own Russia is a 
federation of restless nationalities that might be as inclined to declare 
independence from him soon after he achieved the independence he affects to 
declare from the central government. 
</P>
<P>
Gorbachev has never yet failed to mount an overwhelming majority whenever he 
has put an issue to a parliamentary vote. Given that record, it's hard to 
understand why he failed to stop Yeltsin's ascension by applying his inarguably 
formidable party machine to the job. 
</P>
<P>
The assumption that statesmen know what they are doing is one of the more 
common errors in analysis of their policies. But if we grant that Gorbachev 
knew the consequences of inaction, there is no plausible way to explain this 
instance of it except as a calculated decision to let Yeltsin have center stage 
and trust him for a series of pratfalls. That could turn out to be a shrewd 
stroke, because Yeltsin appears to have started without much plan of his own 
and at once betrayed signs of proceeding according to what may have been 
Gorbachev's. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
