<P>
'SUICIDE MACHINE' USER IS EULOGIZED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Friends and relatives gathered at the First Unitarian Church in Portland, Ore., 
for a memorial service for Janet Elaine Adkins, 54, who used a controversial 
machine to commit suicide last week in Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
Adkins had planned the joyful, hourlong ceremony before traveling to Michigan, 
where Dr. Jack Kevorkian hooked her up to the suicide machine he invented. She 
touched a button, releasing an anesthetic followed by a lethal injection. 
Seconds later, she was dead. Adkins was suffering from Alzheimer's disease and 
feared mental deterioration. 
</P>
