<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEEKEND VIOLENCE LEAVES 2 DEAD, 4 HURT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVID SMOLLAR, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A rash of shootings and stabbings in the San Diego area late Saturday and early 
Sunday left two persons dead and four wounded, police said. 
</P>
<P>
The violence included another shooting in the dark canyons near the 
U.S.-Mexican border. 
</P>
<P>
In addition, a major traffic accident on California 79 near Aguanga on the 
Riverside County line Sunday afternoon killed three people, the San Diego 
County coroner's office reported. There were no other details available late 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
An undocumented alien, Octavio Calderon, was shot once in the back as he walked 
along Old Monument Road about a half-mile north of the U.S.-Mexican border at 
11:50 p.m. Saturday night, San Diego Police reported. Officers heard six shots 
in the 3200 block of Old Monument Road shortly before finding Calderon. He was 
taken by Life Flight helicopter to UCSD Medical Center, where he was reported 
in serious condition late Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
Police reported that Leonardo Cabrera, 22, died at UCSD Medical Center early 
Sunday morning, after being shot three times about 10 p.m. Saturday in the 400 
block of 33rd Street in Southeast San Diego. His assailants were believed to be 
two men in a gray compact car. A police spokesman said witnesses told 
authorities that the shooting occurred during what appeared to be a drug 
transaction. 
</P>
<P>
A second Latino man in his late teens or early 20s, who had not been identified 
by the coroner's office, was killed by a single gunshot near the corner of 21st 
and Market streets about 1 a.m. Sunday by unknown attackers, the police 
spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
Five minutes later, an unidentified transvestite reportedly showed up at a 
store at 24th and Market streets with a single gunshot wound in the upper right 
arm. The spokesman said it was not clear whether the two shootings were 
related. 
</P>
<P>
Just before midnight Saturday, Tilford Raven was found lying on the sidewalk 
near 48th and Market streets in Southeast San Diego with a stab wound, police 
said. Raven told police that several people "came out of nowhere" and stabbed 
him. The police spokesman said Raven was taken to Physicians &amp; Surgeons 
Hospital, but an emergency room nurse refused to release any information Sunday 
concerning him. 
</P>
<P>
In a second stabbing, Lane Johnson, 41, told police he was knifed in the left 
lower back by two men as he walked along Ocean View Boulevard in Southeast San 
Diego about 1 a.m. Johnson called police from his home in the 300 block of 
South 36th Street and was taken to UCSD Medical Center, where he was reported 
in fair condition Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
In Escondido, police reported that 18-year-old Mariano Orozco was shot in the 
leg during a fight in the 500 block of north Grape Street shortly after 2 a.m. 
He was treated at Palomar Medical Center and released. No suspects have been 
arrested, police said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA061190-0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 232104 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
June 11, 1990, Monday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 12; Column 3; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
411 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY PERSPECTIVE; 
</P>
<P>
SUDDENLY HE HAD A CREDIBILITY PROBLEM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For the past 15 years, the Fair Housing Council of Orange County has worn two 
important hats. With the help of funds from the cities and county government, 
the nonprofit council has fought discrimination in housing at the same time it 
has helped resolve disputes between tenants and landlords. It is that second 
mission that has proved troublesome for David T. Quezada, the 40-year-old 
executive director who was suspended without pay last week. 
</P>
<P>
Speaking of hats, Quezada discovered for himself in recent weeks just how 
complicated things can get when you wear more than one. In addition to being 
the executive director of the council, he allowed himself to fall into a 
category fraught with potential awkwardness and embarrassment: He's a landlord, 
too. 
</P>
<P>
The council's board chairman gives Quezada high marks for his consistent record 
as an advocate for tenants rights. He runs an organization with enough 
credibility in Fullerton, to cite one place, that the agency is where the 
city's code enforcement officer refers tenants who have problems getting 
landlords to fix code violations. 
</P>
<P>
No wonder, then, that a city inspector was surprised when she looked at a 
duplex on East Truslow Avenue that had rotten floors, cracked windows and 
leaking plumbing and learned that the owner was the executive director of the 
county's Fair Housing Council. A check of city records also turned up an 
illegal third rental unit in the back of the duplex. 
</P>
<P>
Quezada later said he had heard no complaints until he tried to evict tenants 
from one of the three units in the building so that he could convert the 
building back to a legal, two-unit complex. Yet the executive director of an 
organization pledged to resolving landlord-tenant problems can ill-afford to 
get caught up in such a dispute. 
</P>
<P>
Quezada's triplex masquerading as a duplex became the focus of a joint 
inspection by the Orange County Health Department, the city Fire Department and 
the Building Department. That kind of attention a Fair Housing Council doesn't 
need. Both the director and his board were embarrassed, as they should have 
been, and he was called on the carpet. 
</P>
<P>
The board's decision to suspend Quezada without pay until he corrected 
violations was fair enough, considering the high marks he has received for his 
work. Yet it should be clear to him now what should have been obvious in the 
first place. You can't wear the hat of a fair-housing advocate when you wear 
another as slumlord. 
</P>
</TEXT>
