<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD; 
</P>
<P>
AFRICA WARNED OF DESTRUCTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MARRAKECH, Morocco 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The head of the U.N. food agency warned Africa today that it is on the path to 
total destruction of its natural resources. 
</P>
<P>
Edouard Saouma, director general of the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization, 
told an agency conference on Africa that the continent faces "an extremely 
serious threat of accelerated, continent-wide environmental decline with the 
inevitable outcome in the long term of total depletion." 
</P>
<P>
In an opening speech to delegates from 51 states, he said there is a widening 
gap between agricultural production, which grew at 2% over the last decade, and 
population, which grew at 3%. 
</P>
<P>
At the three-day conference the FAO will outline a series of remedial steps for 
which it has budgeted $527 million in 1990-91. Land reclamation, soil 
conservation and increasing food production by training farmers in more 
efficient methods will be the focus of the FAO plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
