<P>
ANJELICA HUSTON GAINS SPOTLIGHT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For 17 years Anjelica Huston lived in the limelight of her lover, Jack 
Nicholson. But now, with Nicholson out of the picture, she is stepping into her 
own spotlight. 
</P>
<P>
Their erratic relationship came to an end last year when Nicholson had an 
affair with a former waitress, Rebecca Broussard, who had Nicholson's baby in 
April. 
</P>
<P>
Huston, who won an Oscar for her role in "Prizzi's Honor," said her recent 
screen work has mirrored and helped manage her life. 
</P>
<P>
She appeared in "Crimes and Misdemeanors" as a woman rejected by her married 
lover. When she finished "Enemies, A Love Story," in which she plays a woman 
whose husband has a child by another woman, she went home to the harsh reality 
of Nicholson's infidelity. 
</P>
<P>
"That very much reflected what was to go on in my life directly after I came 
back to Los Angeles after the movie. That was pretty close to the bone," she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
Huston said she doesn't know if she is ready to be part of a couple again. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm selfish and opinionated," she said. "I think I follow less than I used to. 
It's hard for me to sit and nod my head at repeated stories anymore." 
</P>
</TEXT>
